{
  "Alfred Wegener proposed continental drift in 1912. The driving mechanism is now known to be:": "",
  "Erosion, particularly regarding": "",
  "Lunar tides, particularly": "",
  "Gravity alone as typically": "",
  "Mantle convection driving plate tectonics": "",
  "Wegener could not explain how continents moved. We now know that convection currents in the mantle, along with ridge push and slab pull forces, drive tectonic plates across Earth's surface.": "",
  "The supercontinent Pangaea existed approximately _____ million years ago.": "",
  "250-300": "",
  "1,000": "",
  "100": "",
  "50": "",
  "Pangaea assembled about 300 million years ago and began breaking apart roughly 200 million years ago. Fossil, geological, and paleoclimate evidence from multiple continents supports its existence.": "",
  "Matching Mesosaurus fossils found on both South America and Africa support continental drift because:": "",
  "It is merely a coincidence": "",
  "This freshwater reptile could not cross oceans, so the continents must have been joined": "",
  "The fossils were planted by researchers": "",
  "The animal could swim across oceans": "",
  "Mesosaurus was a small freshwater reptile that could not survive in salt water or cross thousands of kilometers of ocean. Finding its fossils on both continents is strong evidence that South America and Africa were once connected.": "",
  "At a divergent boundary, plates move _____ and new crust is _____.": "",
  "Apart; created": "",
  "Past each other; unchanged": "",
  "Together; created": "",
  "Together; destroyed": "",
  "At divergent boundaries, tectonic plates move apart and magma rises from below to fill the gap, creating new oceanic crust. Mid-ocean ridges are the most prominent examples of divergent boundaries.": "",
  "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge is an example of a:": "",
  "Hotspot": "",
  "Divergent boundary": "",
  "Convergent boundary": "",
  "Transform boundary": "",
  "The Mid-Atlantic Ridge is a divergent plate boundary where the North American and Eurasian plates (and the South American and African plates) are moving apart. New oceanic crust is continuously formed here.": "",
  "When an oceanic plate converges with a continental plate, the oceanic plate:": "",
  "Pushes the continental plate downward": "",
  "Remains stationary": "",
  "Subducts beneath the continental plate because it is denser": "",
  "Floats above the continental plate": "",
  "Oceanic crust is denser than continental crust (basalt vs. granite), so at a convergent boundary the denser oceanic plate dives beneath the lighter continental plate in a process called subduction.": "",
  "The San Andreas Fault is a _____ boundary.": "",
  "Divergent": "",
  "Transform": "",
  "Convergent": "",
  "The San Andreas Fault is a transform boundary where the Pacific Plate and North American Plate slide horizontally past each other. This produces frequent earthquakes but no volcanic activity.": "",
  "Magnetic striping on the ocean floor provides evidence for seafloor spreading because:": "",
  "They are randomly distributed": "",
  "Symmetric magnetic reversals on both sides of ridges show new crust forms and moves outward": "",
  "The stripes indicate water depth": "",
  "The stripes are colorful and visible from satellites": "",
  "As new crust forms at mid-ocean ridges, minerals in the cooling rock align with Earth's magnetic field. When the field reverses, the magnetic signature flips. The symmetric pattern on both sides of the ridge proves crust spreads outward.": "",
  "Ocean crust near mid-ocean ridges is _____ than crust far from ridges.": "",
  "Denser": "",
  "Younger": "",
  "Thicker": "",
  "Older": "",
  "New oceanic crust is created at mid-ocean ridges and moves outward over time. Therefore crust near the ridge is youngest, and age increases with distance from the ridge. The oldest oceanic crust is about 200 million years old.": "",
  "Tectonic plates move at rates of approximately:": "",
  "They do not move": "",
  "Kilometers per year": "",
  "Meters per day": "",
  "Centimeters per year": "",
  "Tectonic plates move at rates of about 1-15 centimeters per year, roughly the speed at which fingernails grow. This slow but persistent motion drives earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, and mountain building over millions of years.": "",
  "What is continental drift?": "",
  "The rise and fall of sea levels during ice ages": "",
  "The hypothesis proposed by Wegener that continents have moved across Earth's surface over geological time": "",
  "The erosion of continental edges by wave action": "",
  "The process of ocean currents moving sand along coastlines": "",
  "Continental drift was the hypothesis proposed by Alfred Wegener in 1912 that the continents were once joined together and have since moved to their current positions. It was later incorporated into the broader theory of plate tectonics.": "",
  "What is seafloor spreading?": "",
  "The spreading of sediment across the ocean floor by deep currents": "",
  "The widening of beaches due to wave deposition": "",
  "The expansion of the ocean floor due to thermal heating": "",
  "The process by which new oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges as plates move apart and magma rises to fill the gap": "",
  "Seafloor spreading is the process where new oceanic crust is created at mid-ocean ridges. As tectonic plates diverge, magma rises from the mantle, cools, and solidifies, adding new material to both plates symmetrically.": "",
  "What is subduction?": "",
  "The upward movement of magma through a volcanic vent": "",
  "The formation of new crust at a mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "The process by which one tectonic plate descends beneath another into the mantle at a convergent boundary": "",
  "The process by which two plates slide horizontally past each other": "",
  "Subduction occurs at convergent boundaries where a denser plate (usually oceanic) dives beneath a less dense plate into the mantle. This process creates deep ocean trenches, volcanic arcs, and is responsible for recycling oceanic crust.": "",
  "What is a transform boundary?": "",
  "A boundary where plates collide and one is pushed beneath the other": "",
  "A boundary where plates pull apart and new crust forms": "",
  "A boundary where plates slide horizontally past each other, producing earthquakes but no volcanism": "",
  "A boundary where a plate passes over a hotspot in the mantle": "",
  "Transform boundaries are places where tectonic plates slide horizontally past each other. Because no crust is created or destroyed, volcanism does not occur, but the friction between the plates generates frequent earthquakes. The San Andreas Fault is a famous example.": "",
  "What is the Ring of Fire?": "",
  "A horseshoe-shaped zone of intense volcanic and seismic activity encircling the Pacific Ocean, caused by subduction zones": "",
  "A chain of volcanoes in the Atlantic Ocean": "",
  "A ring of hot springs found only in Iceland": "",
  "The boundary between Earth's core and mantle": "",
  "The Ring of Fire is a 40,000-km horseshoe-shaped zone around the Pacific Ocean where about 75% of the world's active volcanoes and 90% of earthquakes occur. It is defined by subduction zones where oceanic plates dive beneath continental or other oceanic plates.": "",
  "What is a divergent boundary?": "",
  "A boundary between continental and oceanic crust within the same plate": "",
  "A boundary where plates collide head-on": "",
  "A boundary where plates grind past each other sideways": "",
  "A boundary where two tectonic plates move apart, allowing magma to rise and create new crust": "",
  "A divergent boundary is where tectonic plates move apart from each other. As they separate, hot mantle material rises to fill the gap, creating new crust. Examples include mid-ocean ridges and continental rift zones like the East African Rift.": "",
  "What does 'Pangaea' mean?": "",
  "Ring of fire, referring to the Pacific volcanic zone in the context of this analysis": "",
  "First plate, referring to the original tectonic plate under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Ancient ocean, particularly regarding comes under the given assumptions": "",
  "All lands, referring to the supercontinent that contained all of Earth's major landmasses roughly 250-300 million years ago": "",
  "Pangaea comes from the Greek words 'pan' (all) and 'gaia' (Earth/land), meaning 'all lands.' It was the supercontinent that existed during the late Paleozoic and early Mesozoic eras before breaking apart into the continents we know today.": "",
  "What is a convergent boundary?": "",
  "A boundary where plates slide past each other horizontally": "",
  "A boundary where two tectonic plates collide, leading to subduction, mountain building, or volcanic arcs": "",
  "A boundary where plates separate and new material fills the gap": "",
  "A location where a mantle plume creates a volcano within a plate": "",
  "A convergent boundary forms where two plates move toward each other. Depending on the plate types, the result can be subduction (oceanic-oceanic or oceanic-continental), mountain building (continental-continental), or volcanic island arcs.": "",
  "What is a hotspot in plate tectonics?": "",
  "The point where an earthquake originates underground": "",
  "The warmest region of the ocean near the equator": "",
  "An area at a plate boundary where magma erupts": "",
  "A volcanic region fed by a stationary mantle plume, over which a tectonic plate moves to create a chain of volcanoes": "",
  "A hotspot is a volcanic region created by a relatively stationary mantle plume that provides a persistent source of magma. As a tectonic plate moves over the hotspot, a chain of volcanoes forms, like the Hawaiian Islands.": "",
  "What is magnetic reversal?": "",
  "The loss of a compass needle's magnetism over time": "",
  "A periodic switch in the direction of Earth's magnetic poles, recorded in rocks as they form and cool": "",
  "The daily fluctuation of Earth's magnetic field strength": "",
  "The bending of magnetic field lines near the equator": "",
  "Magnetic reversals are events in which Earth's magnetic north and south poles switch positions. These reversals are recorded in volcanic rocks as they cool, with magnetic minerals aligning to the field at the time of cooling. The pattern of reversals on the ocean floor was key evidence for seafloor spreading.": "",
  "A team of geologists maps the age of ocean floor rocks across the Atlantic Ocean and finds that rocks near the Mid-Atlantic Ridge are very young while rocks near the continental margins are much older. What does this age pattern demonstrate?": "",
  "Rocks near continents are older because continents create rocks faster": "",
  "Erosion destroys younger rocks near continents, leaving only old ones": "",
  "The Atlantic Ocean is shrinking as the ridge collapses": "",
  "New crust is formed at the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and moves outward over time, confirming seafloor spreading": "",
  "The progressive increase in ocean floor age with distance from the ridge is one of the strongest pieces of evidence for seafloor spreading. New crust forms at the ridge and is carried outward like a conveyor belt, so the oldest crust is farthest from the ridge.": "",
  "Iceland is located directly on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and experiences frequent volcanic eruptions and earthquakes. A tourist asks why Iceland is so geologically active compared to most islands. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Iceland sits on a divergent plate boundary where the North American and Eurasian plates are pulling apart, and it also lies over a mantle hotspot": "",
  "Iceland is sinking into the ocean, causing geological stress": "",
  "Iceland is made entirely of coral that reacts to ocean temperature changes": "",
  "The island is too far north and cold temperatures cause rocks to crack": "",
  "Iceland sits atop both the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (a divergent boundary) and a mantle hotspot. This combination of two volcanic sources makes it one of the most geologically active places on Earth, with frequent eruptions, geysers, and earthquakes.": "",
  "GPS measurements show that the Hawaiian Islands are moving northwest at about 7 cm per year relative to a fixed point in the mantle. Meanwhile, the active volcano Kilauea is at the southeastern end of the island chain. How does plate tectonics explain this pattern?": "",
  "The islands were formed by separate volcanic events at different plate boundaries": "",
  "The entire chain of islands is moving toward a new hotspot": "",
  "Ocean currents push the islands northwest over time": "",
  "The Pacific Plate is moving northwest over a stationary hotspot, so the newest volcanic island is always at the southeastern end": "",
  "The Hawaiian island chain formed as the Pacific Plate moves northwest over a stationary mantle hotspot. Each island was once over the hotspot but moved away as the plate carried it northwest. The Big Island with Kilauea is currently over the hotspot and thus the most volcanically active.": "",
  "Two cities on opposite sides of the San Andreas Fault are slowly moving closer together (Los Angeles toward San Francisco). If they are currently about 560 km apart and the plates move at about 5 cm per year, approximately how many millions of years would it take for them to be side-by-side?": "",
  "About 500 years": "",
  "About 11 million years": "",
  "It will never happen because transform faults do not move plates": "",
  "About 100 million years": "",
  "At 5 cm/year, covering 560 km (560,000 m) would take 560,000/0.05 = 11.2 million years. This calculation illustrates how slow plate motion is on a human timescale but how profound its effects are over geological time.": "",
  "A volcanic island arc (like Japan) is located parallel to a deep ocean trench. A student asks why these two features are always found together. What is the tectonic explanation?": "",
  "Both are caused by subduction: the trench marks where one plate dives beneath another, and the volcanic arc forms as the subducting plate releases water that melts overlying mantle rock": "",
  "Volcanic islands push down the ocean floor to create trenches": "",
  "Ocean trenches trap volcanic debris that builds into islands": "",
  "Ocean currents erode the seafloor near volcanic islands creating trenches": "",
  "Ocean trenches and volcanic arcs are both products of subduction. The trench forms where the descending plate bends downward. As the plate sinks deeper, water released from its minerals lowers the melting point of the overlying mantle, generating magma that rises to form a chain of volcanoes.": "",
  "Scientists predict that in 50 million years, the East African Rift will have split the African continent into two separate landmasses with a new ocean between them. What current geological evidence supports this prediction?": "",
  "Satellite images show the two halves moving at 10 meters per year": "",
  "All continents are simultaneously splitting apart due to Earth's expansion": "",
  "Africa is being pushed apart by ocean currents from both sides": "",
  "The rift features active volcanism, frequent earthquakes, a thinning crust, and a widening rift valley, all consistent with continental divergence": "",
  "The East African Rift shows all the signs of continental divergence: a thinning crust, volcanic activity, seismicity, and a widening rift valley. This is an early stage of the same process that separated South America from Africa, eventually creating the Atlantic Ocean.": "",
  "During a natural disaster preparedness meeting, an official claims that California is going to 'fall into the ocean' due to the San Andreas Fault. A geologist corrects this misconception. What is actually happening at the San Andreas Fault?": "",
  "The Pacific and North American plates are sliding horizontally past each other, not pulling apart, so California is moving northwest along the coast, not into the ocean": "",
  "California is being subducted beneath the Pacific Plate according to conventional analysis": "",
  "The fault is pushing California upward, forming new mountains as typically measured in practice": "",
  "California is slowly sinking below sea level, particularly regarding where in most standard conditions": "",
  "The San Andreas Fault is a transform boundary where the Pacific Plate moves northwest relative to the North American Plate. The motion is lateral (side-by-side), not divergent. Western California is slowly moving toward Alaska, not falling into the Pacific Ocean.": "",
  "The Himalayas continue to grow taller by about 5 mm per year. A geology student asks why the mountains are still growing millions of years after the Indian and Eurasian plates first collided. What is the explanation?": "",
  "The mountains are growing because of isostatic rebound from ice age glaciers": "",
  "Glacial deposition adds sediment to the mountain peaks each year": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions keep adding material to the mountain tops": "",
  "The Indian Plate is still actively pushing into the Eurasian Plate, continuing to compress and uplift the crust": "",
  "The Indian Plate is still converging with the Eurasian Plate at about 4-5 cm per year. This ongoing collision continues to compress, fold, and uplift the crust, causing the Himalayas to grow taller. Erosion counteracts some of this growth.": "",
  "Paleontologists discover fossils of the same tropical plant species (Glossopteris) on continents that now have very different climates, including Antarctica, South America, Africa, India, and Australia. How does plate tectonics explain this finding?": "",
  "Seeds of Glossopteris could float across oceans to reach all continents": "",
  "Glossopteris evolved independently on each continent due to similar conditions": "",
  "These continents were once joined as part of Gondwana in a temperate climate zone, and later drifted to their current positions and climates": "",
  "Ancient humans transported Glossopteris seeds between continents": "",
  "Glossopteris was a seed fern that could not have dispersed across wide oceans. Its presence on multiple now-separated continents is strong evidence they were once connected as part of the southern supercontinent Gondwana, situated in a climate zone that supported this vegetation.": "",
  "An engineering firm is designing a pipeline that must cross a plate boundary. The project geologist recommends flexible joints and automated shut-off valves. If the boundary is a transform fault, why are these precautions especially necessary?": "",
  "Transform faults cause the ground to sink, burying the pipeline": "",
  "Transform faults release toxic gases from the mantle": "",
  "Transform faults produce frequent earthquakes with sudden horizontal displacement that could rupture a rigid pipeline": "",
  "Transform faults produce volcanic eruptions that could melt the pipeline": "",
  "Transform faults produce frequent earthquakes with sudden lateral (horizontal) displacement. A rigid pipeline crossing such a fault could be sheared apart during an earthquake. Flexible joints allow the pipeline to accommodate movement, and automated shut-off valves prevent spills if rupture occurs.": ""
}